   <mods:abstract>Encloses copies of his eulogy on James Monroe and an address delivered by
            him to the town inhabitants on the 4th of July last. Has heard of William's intention to
            publish a biography on John Jay; regrets that distance has prevented a better
            acquaintance with his children. An immense disproportion of Franklin's virtues was
            concentrated in prudence; his life exemplifies the line: Nullum Numen abest si sit
            Prudentia. There is a moral philosophy of a higher order than this. He signed the Treaty
            of Peace with Britain but gave Vergennes to understand that the withholding of the
            contents was against his will. He had a "language official, and a language
            confidential." This was never said of Jay; his prudence, though scarcely less than
            Franklin's, had another foundation.</mods:abstract>
